Hey all! Most of you know me as Steadijess, camera operator with speciality in steadicam. ... The pandemic caused so much change in my life, with my health, and my career path. As I'm sure it did the same for everyone else.... Last year, I had to take time off for internal medical reasons. Now I'm back and healed and struggling to find work. Crazy how it all disappears when you need time for yourself! 🙄 Questioning if I should keep following this path.... in the past I've had my ups and downs on set. Most of the time, I've proven that I can create good shots and follow directions. But I always seem to be a "temporary diversity hire." Never really getting offered to come back to crews, or if I couldn't take the job, I don't get a future call back.... honestly I love my job when I get to do it. But now... who wants to hire me? I've called, sent messages, had meetings, and nothing. Do I keep trying to be this person? Do I keep trying to fight for my place in an industry that doesn't want me to stay? Should I disappear like the many steadicam women before me? I'm about to lose my medical insurance and I've just reached halfway marker in my timeline of life. I feel like I have nothing to show for many years of hard work.... I guess my midlife crisis is underway. Anyways... I'm venting. Available for hire. Or not. Thanks for advice, and the support. Blessings to you all! #questioninglife #steadijess #availableforhire #steadical #local600 #cameradept

This old friend came by recently to grab some cases that my mentors were giving away at Tyler Mount. You all know the man behind CINEMILLED @cinemilled Pedro Guimaraes! Was very nice to catch up! Time flies, it was around 2010 when I first met Pedro while he was flying 3D Steadicam rigs and I was helping build 3D rigs before I got my first steadicam. Pedro is extremely supportive to so many people in the industry and I'm so grateful to witness his achievements over the years. Proud of you Pedro @m3pedro! My 3rd day in Ireland. I'm so grateful to be back in one of my favorite countries. So healthy for me being here. All my problems fell off when the plane landed. With the Actors still striking in Los Angeles many of us crew members are out of work or even get a day or two a month. Sadly it is not enough to pay bills. So I decide to pack up my shit and leave LA for rest of the year. It's actually cheaper to  cash in my SkyMiles, fly to Europe, visit with friends, and housesit. No point of hanging in a city where everyone is sad and depressed. I can't live in that mental state anymore this year. So here I am solo traveling to the most beautiful places. Staytuned for pics and videos of my adventures. I'm even meeting up with my European filmmaker friends. Very excited and very grateful I can do this! 🙏🏼💜 #steadijess #travel #keephopealive #iloveireland #iloveeurope #solotravel #solotraveler #filmmakerlife #grateful #cahircastle #ireland

This is the Finnich Glen, better known as the Devil’s Pulpit. 

Historically, the Devil’s Pulpit was the name used for the mushroom-like rock in the middle of the stream. According to folklore, it was where the Devil stood to address his followers. 

Other stories  indicate that it was also a site of great importance to Druids. Later on, it has been said that the rock was a site for the execution of witches as well. 

Either way it was likely the ominous red coloring of the stream was the cause for all these dark folklore stories to come about. In modern times, the whole of Finnich Glen is referred to as the Devil’s Pulpit.

Some of you may also recognise it from Outlander where it features as “Liar’s spring”

If someone tries to lie after drinking from Liar’s Spring, their throat will burn!

Huge thanks to the amazing @steadijess for the amazing footage, give her a follow if you don’t already!

sources:unusualplaces.org
